<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-220-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 220 020.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 5 1990 v9 n5 p70(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Justice officials investigating another 1984 Army contract.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Infonet Services Corp. (contracts).andO;Topic:     InvestigationsDefense ContractsLegal IssuesUnited States. ArmyUnited States. Department of Justice.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Justice Officials Investigating Another 1984 Army ContractandM;For the second time since last fall, the Justice Department is investigatingan Army computer contract awarded in 1984.andP;  The second investigation centerson a remote computing services contract held by Infonet Services Corp., aformer subsidiary of Computer Sciences Corp.andM;Mark Hulkower, a Justice Department spokesman, would neither confirm nor denythat the company is under investigation.andP;  But CSC spokesman WilliamHelmantoler last week confirmed the probe.andM;&quot;CSC has been informed that the U.S.andP;  Justice Department is conducting aninvestigation into a contract awarded in 1984 and performed by CSC's formerInfonet unit,&quot; Helmantoler said.andP;  &quot;CSC is cooperating with thatinvestigation.&quot;andM;Helmantoler said CSC sold Infonet earlier this year.andP;  MCI CommunicationsCorp. bought one-quarter of the company.andP;  A consortium of thetelecommunications agencies of 10 countries in Europe and the Pacific boughtthe other three-quarters, he said.andM;The five-year Army contract &quot;was for remote computing services in support ofthe Army's recruitment and re-enlistment program, Helmantoler said.andP;  Thewhole contract was worth about $32 million.&quot;andM;A congressional employee who would not speak without a promise of anonymitysaid several congressional committees have looked into Army ADP buys in themid-1980s.andM;But there was no evidence that the Infonet investigation is related to therecent indictment of Automated Data Management Inc. of Washington, an 8(a)contractor that received an Army contract in 1984.andM;In January, a grand jury indicted ADM and four of its officers on charges oftax evasion, fraud and providing false information to the government.andM;ADM's contract to sell micros recently expired after five years.andP;  During thattime, Army officials said, the company sold the Army 9,500 microcomputersmade by Wang Laboratories Inc.andP;  ADM's revenues totaled about $85 million, theofficials said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>